mple of the firms wares known to be in existence, which comprises a rather well potted stoneware jug with sprigged hunting scenes applied around its belly. It was not a successful venture, and Bulkeley fades out of the scenario. However, Bent - quite undeterred by the failure of his first venture - went onto make a very astute move: he converted his now defunct potworks into, of all things - a brewery! He utilised the existing plant and converted his pottery oven into a malt kiln. His new partners were James Caldwell, who was a potter in his own right, and James Barrow, a local financier.\r\n\r\nThis second phase of the Hotels life was much more successful and culminated in the creation of a brewing empire worth over a quarter of a million pounds during the last quarter of the nineteenth century. At its height, the name Bent was a household word and the products of the family breweries were known the world over.\r\n\r\nEven so, the early days of the foundation of the brewery were not without their catastrophes. On the evening of September 15th, 1806, the brewery warehouse appears to have suffered serious damage in a devastating fire. One thousand and eighty bushels of malt were destroyed, or to be more exact, the equivalent of forty-four thousand pints.\r\n\r\nHowever, as we now know, the firm survived and prospered until eventually the Bent family sold out their interests to a firm known as Rogers, Baker and Hindle. Eventually, in 1853, a licence was applied for to turn the premises into an Inn. This marked the birth of The Borough Arms Hotel as we now know it. \r\n\r\nThe Inn became very successful, for as well as drawing trade from the Newcastle Railway Station, opposite (no longer in existence), it also benefited from being on the main highway and attracted over 40 carriages a day. Passengers on longer journeys inevitably stayed the night and The Borough Arms flourished as a main focal point of the town.\r\n\r\nToday, the hotel is privately-owned by the Sheikh family. A deeply personal project of love and determination, Mr Sheikh can be found at the hotel most days, working with his dedicated team with one aim in mind: to provide warm, heartfelt hospitality to guests  whether they dine, stay, celebrate, or do business with us'),(2930,289,'_module_builder_history_1_content','field_5dc29a08ca46d'),(2931,289,'module_builder_history_1_button_text',''),(2932,289,'_module_builder_history_1_button_text','field_5dc29a08cc51f'),(2933,289,'module_builder_history_1_button_url',''),(2934,289,'_module_builder_history_1_button_url','field_5dc29a08ce7c9'),(2935,289,'module_builder_history_2_image_and_text_grid_0_image','143'),(2936,289,'_module_builder_history_2_image_and_text_grid_0_image','field_5dc29a0911e2f'),(2937,289,'module_builder_history_2_image_and_text_grid_0_heading','Restaurant'),(2938,289,'_module_builder_history_2_image_and_text_grid_0_heading','field_5dc29a0912ba9'),(2939,289,'module_builder_history_2_image_and_text_grid_0_content',''),(2940,289,'_module_builder_history_2_image_and_text_grid_0_content','field_5dc29a091391e'),(2941,289,'module_builder_history_2_image_and_text_grid_1_image','144'),(2942,289,'_module_builder_history_2_image_and_text_grid_1_image','field_5dc29a0911e2f'),(2943,289,'module_builder_history_2_image_and_text_grid_1_heading','Bar'),(2944,289,'_module_builder_history_2_image_and_text_grid_1_heading','field_5dc29a0912ba9'),(2945,289,'module_builder_history_2_image_and_text_grid_1_content',''),(2946,289,'_module_builder_history_2_image_and_text_grid_1_content','field_5dc29a091391e'),(2947,289,'module_builder_history_2_image_and_text_grid_2_image','247'),(2948,289,'_module_builder_history_2_image_and_text_grid_2_image','field_5dc29a0911e2f'),(2949,289,'module_builder_history_2_image_and_text_grid_2_heading','Weddings'),(2950,289,'_module_builder_history_2_image_and_text_grid_2_heading','field_5dc29a0912ba9'),(2951,289,'module_builder_history_2_image_and_text_grid_2_content',''),(2952,289,'_module_build